{"parse":{"title":"peach","pageid":10037,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Peach}}\n==English==\n[[Image:Autumn Red peaches.jpg|thumb|Autumn Red '''peaches''' (noun sense 2).]]\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈpiːt͡ʃ/|[ˈpɪi̯t͡ʃ]}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-peach.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{rhymes|en|iːtʃ|s=1}}\n* {{hyph|en|peach}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymon|en|id=tree|:inh|enm:peche|tree=1}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|peche}}, borrowed from {{der|en|fro|pesche}} ({{cog|fr|pêche}}), {{der|en|la-vul|*pessica}} (cf. Medieval Latin {{m|la|pesca}}) from {{der|en|la-lat|persica}}, from Classical {{der|en|la|mālum}} {{m|la|persicum}}, from {{der|en|grc|[[μῆλον|μᾶλον]] [[Περσικός|περσικόν]]|t=Persian apple}}. Displaced {{cog|enm|persogȝe}}, from {{cog|ang|persoc}}, ultimately from the same Latin root above.\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|~}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|Q13189}}{{lb|en|countable}} Any tree of species {{taxfmt|Prunus persica|species}}, [[native]] to [[China]] and now widely [[cultivate]]d throughout [[temperate]] regions, having pink flowers and edible fruit.\n#: {{synonyms|en|peach tree}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=M. Combles|title=A Treatise Upon the Culture of Peach Trees|year=1768|page=8|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=7ElAAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA8|passage=I think it the best way to plant the fifteen sorts, and the hard '''Peaches''' I have mentioned, in the same order as they stand in the list.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Thomas Bridgeman|title=The Young Gardener’s Assistant|year=1840|page=136|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=bW1KAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA316|passage=Several attempts have been made to class the varieties of '''Peaches''' and Nectarines by the leaf and flower, as well as the fruit.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Raymond Earl Storie|title=Soil Survey, the Pixley Area, California|year=1942|volume=1|page=11|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=Asg_AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA11|passage=Scattered plantings of peaches are maintained on the light-textured deep alluvial soils of the Foster, Cajon, Hanford, Hesperia, and Greenfield series west of Porterville, near Woodville, Poplar, Sausalito School, and farther south along the Kern County boundary line north of Delano.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Melissa Walker|title=The New Encyclopedia of Southern Culture|year=2014|volume=11|page=183|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=LyiaAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA183|passage=State universities and U.S. Department of Agriculture facilities have largely replaced the private state and national pomological and horticultural organizations as the primary researchers for '''peach''' cultivation.}}\n# {{senseid|en|fruit}}{{lb|en|countable|uncountable}} Soft juicy [[stone fruit]] of the peach tree, having yellow flesh, downy, red-tinted yellow skin, and a deeply sculptured pit or stone containing a single seed.\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Hester Lynch Piozzi|title=Observations and Reflections Made in the Course of a Journey Through France, Italy, and Germany|year=1789|volume=II|page=191|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=SH9CAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA191|passage=[A]nd that the English should eat '''peaches''' in May, and green pease in October, sounds to Italian ears as a miracle; they comfort themselves, however, by saying that they must be very insipid, while we know that fruits forced by strong fire are at least many of them higher in flavour than those produced by sun {{...}}}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=The American Housewife and Kitchen Directory|year=1869|page=104|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=oHMEAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA104|passage=When dissolved, stir it up well, and put in the '''peaches''', without crowding them, and boil them slowly about twenty minutes.}}\n#* {{RQ:T. S. Eliot Prufrock|page=15|passage=Shall I part my hair behind? Do I dare eat a '''peach'''? / I shall wear white flannel trousers, and walk upon the beach.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Jasper Woodroof|title=Commercial Fruit Processing|year=2012|page=103|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=OmoyBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA103|passage=Boiling water or steam loosens the peel of very ripe '''peaches''', especially freestone or melting-flesh types, in 10–30 sec.}}\n# {{senseid|en|Q5148721}}{{lb|en|uncountable}} A light yellow-red colour.\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Thomas Love|title=The Art of Cleaning, Dyeing, Scouring and Finishing, etc|year=1854|page=242|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=1TNdAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA242|passage=To dye one chip bonnet '''peach''' colour, put four ounces of cudbear in one gallon of water, make it boil, and put one ounce of soda in the liquor.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Lila Fretz|title=Hooking Rugs: Storey’s Country Wisdom Bulletin|year=1990|page=27|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=YcxTApG_ZOIC&pg=PA27|passage=If the dye is for a light color such as '''peach''', more dry dye could be used.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Kim Eichler-Messmer|title=Modern Color—An Illustrated Guide to Dyeing Fabric for Modern Quilts|year=2013|page=61|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=WbS1AQAAQBAJ&pg=PA61|passage=''Circle Quilt'' throw in '''peach''' and green}}\n#: {{color panel|FFCF9D}}\n# {{lb|en|countable|informal}} A particularly admirable or pleasing person or thing.\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Lucile Brewer|title=Fourteen Peach Delicacies|magazine=The Delineator|month=September|year=1922|volume=101|page=58|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=uGM6AQAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA58|passage=How did the common expressions \"She's a '''peach'''!\" and \"He has a '''peach''' of a job!\" arise if not because the peach of all fruits is a symbol of perfection?}}\n#* {{quote-song|en|artist=w:The Stranglers|title=Peaches|album=Rattus Norvegicus|year=1977|passage=Walking on the beaches / looking at the '''peaches'''}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Paul L. Mariani|title=Dream Song: The Life of John Berryman|year=1996|page=30|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=OfE0wMKORCYC&pg=PA30|passage=Except for the loss of Uncle Jack's income, his mother's growing disenchantment with her domestic arrangements, and the deepening Depression, it was a '''peach''' of a time for Berryman.}}\n#* {{RQ:Guardian|author=Amy Lawrence|title=Arsenal's Gervinho enjoys the joy of six against lowly Southampton|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2012/sep/15/arsenal-southampton-premier-league|date=15 September 2012|passage=Arsenal's dominance was reflected in a flurry of goals before half-time – three in six minutes: first, Podolski turned the screw with a '''peach''' of a free-kick; then Gervinho accelerated on to Mikel Arteta's beautifully crafted pass and beat Davis at his near post with conviction; and finally Southampton's defence unspooled completely when Gervinho broke to release Gibbs, whose return ball cannoned off Nathaniel Clyne for Southampton's second own goal of a sobering afternoon.}}\n# {{lb|en|euphemestic|often in plural}} [[buttock|Buttock]] or [[bottom]].\n#* {{quote-song|en|year=1977|artist={{w|the Stranglers}}|title={{w|Peaches (The Stranglers song)|Peaches}}|text=Down on the beaches, just look at all the '''peaches'''}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=[[w:Snooki|Nicole “Snooki” Polizzi]]|title=A Shore Thing|year=2011|passage=Gia danced around a little, shaking her '''peaches''' for show. She shook it hard. Too hard. In the middle of a shimmy, her stomach cramped. A fart slipped out. A loud one. And stinky.}}\n\n=====Hypernyms=====\n* [[Thesaurus:fruit|fruit]]\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|peachery|peachish|peachlet\n|cling peach|doughnut peach|longevity peach|peach fruit moth|peach fuzz|peach tree|peach water\n|[[African peach]] ({{taxlink|Sarcocephalus latifolius|species}})\n|{{vern|Anderson's peachbrush}} ({{taxlink|Prunus andersonii|species}})\n|[[belly-up peach]] ({{taxfmt|Prunus persica subsp. platycarpa|subspecies}})\n|bloom is off the peach\n|blush is off the peach|peach of immortality|peach phony disease|phony peach disease\n|[[Chinese peach]] ({{taxfmt|Prunus persica subsp. platycarpa|subspecies}})\n|clingstone peach\n|[[custard peach]] ({{taxfmt|Prunus persica subsp. platycarpa|subspecies}})\n|{{vern|desert peach}} ({{taxlink|Prunus andersonii|species}})\n|[[donut peach]] ({{taxfmt|Prunus persica subsp. platycarpa|subspecies}})\n|[[flat peach]] ({{taxfmt|Prunus persica subsp. platycarpa|subspecies}})\n|{{vern|freestone peach}}\n|freeze peach\n|{{vern|fuzzless peach}} ({{taxlink|Prunus persica var. nucipersica|variety}}, {{taxlink|Prunus persica var. nectarina|variety}})|peach pit,peach-pit\n|{{vern|green peach aphid}} ({{taxlink|Myzus persicae|species}})\n|[[Guinea peach]] ({{taxlink|Sarcocephalus latifolius|species}})\n|[[hat peach]] ({{taxfmt|Prunus persica subsp. platycarpa|subspecies}})\n|{{vern|Indian peach}}\n|[[Jupiter peach]] ({{taxfmt|Prunus persica subsp. platycarpa|subspecies}})\n|little peach\n|{{vern|lesser peach tree borer}} ({{taxlink|Synanthedon pictipes|species}})\n|[[pan tao peach]] ({{taxfmt|Prunus persica subsp. platycarpa|subspecies}})\n|[[paraguayo peach]] ({{taxfmt|Prunus persica subsp. platycarpa|subspecies}})\n|peacharita\n|[[peach bark beetle]] ({{taxlink|Phloeotribus liminaris|species}})\n|{{vern|peach borer}}\n|peach blossom\n|Peach County\n|peacherino\n|{{vern|peach-fronted parakeet}}, {{vern|peach-fronted conure}} ({{taxlink|Eupsittula aurea|species}})\n|{{vern|peach fruit borer}} ({{taxlink|Carpasina niponesis|species}})\n|{{vern|peach-leaf willow}}, [[peachleaf willow]] ({{taxlink|Salix amygdaloides|species}})\n|peach leaf curl\n|peach melba\n|{{vern|peach oak}} ({{taxlink|Quercus phellos|species}})\n|[[peach palm]] ({{taxfmt|Bactris gasipaes|species}})\n|{{vern|peach-potato aphid}} ({{taxlink|Myzus persicae|species}})\n|{{vern|peach thorn}} ({{taxlink|Lycium cooperi|species}})\n|{{vern|peach twig borer}} ({{taxlink|Anarsia lineatella|species}})\n|peachblow\n|peachbush\n|peachen\n|{{vern|peacherine}}\n|peaches and cream\n|peachfuzz\n|peaching\n|peachleaf\n|[[peachleaf bellflower]] ({{taxlink|Campanula persicifolia|species}})\n|peachless\n|peachlike\n|{{vern|peach snailfish}} ({{taxlink|Allocareproctus tanix|species}})\n|{{vern|peachskin snailfish}} ({{taxlink|Careproctus scottae|species}})\n|Peach Springs\n|peachtini\n|peachtree\n|peachwood\n|peachy\n|peachy keen\n|{{vern|pickle peach}}\n|[[pita peach]] ({{taxfmt|Prunus persica subsp. platycarpa|subspecies}})\n|[[plum peach]]\n|{{vern|press peach}}\n|[[Saturn peach]] ({{taxfmt|Prunus persica subsp. platycarpa|subspecies}})\n|[[saucer peach]] ({{taxfmt|Prunus persica subsp. platycarpa|subspecies}})\n|[[sea peach]] ({{taxlink|Halocynthia|genus}} spp.)\n|[[Sierra Leone peach]] ({{taxlink|Sarcocephalus latifolius|species}})\n|{{vern|smallflower peachbrush}} ({{taxlink|Prunus minutiflora|species}})\n|sweetcap peach\n|{{vern|Texas peachbrush}} ({{taxlink|Prunus texana|species}})\n|[[UFO peach]] ({{taxfmt|Prunus persica subsp. platycarpa|subspecies}})\n|[[wolf's peach]] ({{taxfmt|Solanum lycopersicum|species}})\n}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|bor=1|abe|biches}} {{i|from the plural {{m|en|peaches}}}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|arp|biisib|unc=1}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|bn|পীচ}} {{i|probably}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|hai|píichas}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|ms|pic}} {{i|probably}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|mi|pītiti|unc=1}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|sw|pichi}} {{i|probably}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|th|พีช}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|tree}}\n* Abkhaz: {{t|ab|атамаҵла}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t|af|perskeboom}}\n* Aramaic:\n*: Assyrian Neo-Aramaic: {{t|aii|ܐܝܼܠܵܢܵܐ ܕܚܵܘܚܵܐ|tr=īlana d-ḳawḳa|m}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|դեղձենի}}\n* Aromanian: {{t|rup|chearsic|m}}, {{t|rup|hearhic|m}}\n* Asturian: {{t+|ast|pescal|f}}\n* Basque: {{t|eu|mertxikondo}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|пра́скова|f}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|presseguer|m}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|桃樹|tr=táoshù}}\n* Cornish: {{t|kw|aval gwlanek}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|broskvoň|f}}, {{t+|cs|broskev|f}} {{qualifier|informal}}\n* Danish: {{t|da|ferskentræ|n}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|perzikboom|m}}, {{t+|nl|perzikenboom|m}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|persikka}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|pêcher|