{{t+|th|ท้อ|tr=tɔ́ɔ}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|şeftali}}, {{t+|tr|alıç}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|пе́рсик|m}}, {{t|uk|[[пе́рсиковий|пе́рсикове]] [[де́рево]]|n}}\n* Unami: {{t|unm|pilkëshakw}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|đào}}\n* Volapük: {{t|vo|pärsigabim}}, {{t|vo|pärsigep}}\n* Welsh: {{t|cy|coeden eirin gwlanog|f}}\n* Zazaki: {{t|zza|xewxêr|f}}\n* Zulu: {{t|zu|umpetshisi}} {{qualifier|nc 3}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|fruit}}\n* Abkhaz: {{t|ab|атама}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t+|af|perske}}\n* Alabama: {{t|akz|takkola}}\n* Albanian: {{t+|sq|pjeshkë}}\n* Amharic: {{t|am|ኮክ}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|خَوْخ|f-p}} {{qualifier|collective}}, {{t|ar|خَوْخَة|f}} {{qualifier|singular}}, {{t|ar|دُرَّاق|m}}, {{t|ar|فِرْسِك|m}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{t|arz|خوخ|m|tr=ḵōḵ}} {{qualifier|collective}}, {{t|arz|خوحة|f|tr=ḵōḵa}} (''[[singulative]]'')\n*: Hijazi Arabic: {{t|acw|خوخ|m-p|tr=ḵōḵ}}\n*: Moroccan Arabic: {{t|ary|خوخ|tr=ḵūḵ}}\n*: South Levantine Arabic: {{t|ajp|دراق|m|tr=dirrāʕ}}\n* Aragonese: {{t|an|malacatón|m}}, {{t+|an|presiego|m}}\n* Aramaic:\n*: Assyrian Neo-Aramaic: {{t|aii|ܚܵܘܚܵܐ|tr=ḳawḳa|m}}\n*: Mandaic: {{t|mid|ࡊࡀࡅࡊࡀ|m|tr=ḵawḵā}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|դեղձ}}\n* Aromanian: {{t|rup|chearsicã|f}}, {{t|rup|hearhicã|f}}\n* Asturian: {{t+|ast|piescu|m}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t+|az|şaftalı}}, {{t+|az|hulu}}\n* Basque: {{t+|eu|mertxika}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|пе́рсік|m}}\n* Bengali: {{t|bn|পীচ}}\n* Breton: {{t+|br|pechez}} ''collective noun'' {{t+|br|pechezenn|f}} {{g|s}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|пра́скова|f}}\n* Burmese: {{t+|my|မက်မွန်}}\n* Carpathian Rusyn: {{t|rue|броскы́ня|f}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|préssec|m}}, {{t+|ca|melicotó|m}} {{qualifier|Mallorca}}\n* Cherokee: {{t|chr|ᏆᏅ}}\n* Chickasaw: {{t|cic|takolo}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{t+|yue|桃|tr=tou4-2}}, {{t|yue|桃子|tr=tou4 zi2}}, {{t|yue|蜜桃|tr=mat6 tou4}}\n*: Eastern Min: {{t|cdo|桃|tr=to}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|桃|tr=táo}}, {{t+|cmn|桃子|tr=táozi}}\n* Choctaw: {{t|cho|takkon}}\n* Cornish: {{t|kw|aval gwlanek|f}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|broskev|f}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|fersken|c}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|perzik|m}}\n* Egyptian: {{t-check-egy|dpḥ n prs|m|h=d:p-H-M1-n-p:r-s-N25}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+|eo|persiko}}\n* Estonian: {{t+|et|virsik}}\n* Faroese: {{t|fo|ferska|f}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|persikka}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|pêche|f}}\n* Frisian:\n*: North Frisian: {{t|frr|Fersk|m}} {{qualifier|Sylt}}\n*: West Frisian: {{t|fy|perzik|c}}\n* Friulian: {{t|fur|piersul}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|pexego|m}}, {{t+|gl|pavía|f}}\n* Ge'ez: {{t|gez|ኮክ}}\n* Georgian: {{t+|ka|ატამი}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Pfirsich|m}}\n*: Alemannic German: {{t|gsw|Fërsich|m}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|ροδάκινο|n}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|περσικόν|n}}, {{t|grc|δωράκιον|n}}\n*: Pontic Greek: {{t|pnt|ροδάκινον}}\n* Greenlandic: {{t|kl|ferskeni}}\n* Haitian Creole: {{t|ht|pèch}}\n* Hawaiian: {{t|haw|koukī}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|אֲפַרְסֵק|m|tr=afarsék}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|आड़ू}}, {{t+|hi|शफतालु}}, {{t|hi|शफ़तालु}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|őszibarack}}, {{t+|hu|barack}}\n* Hunsrik: {{t|hrx|Persch|f|m}}, {{t|hrx|fërsich|m}}, {{t|hrx|phërx|m}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|ferskja|f}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|persik}}, {{t+|id|kesemek}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|péitseog|f}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|pesca|f}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|桃|tr=もも, momo}}\n* Kabyle: {{t|kab|taxuxet|f}}, {{t|kab|lxux}}\n* Kaitag: {{t|xdq|кьвя́рче}}\n* Kashmiri: {{t|ks|ژٕنُن}}\n* Kazakh: {{t|kk|шабдалы}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|복숭아}}\n* Kumyk: {{t|kum|шаптал|tr=şaptal}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{t+|kmr|xox|f}}, {{t+|kmr|şeftalî|f}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{t+|ky|шабдалы}}\n* Ladino: {{t|lad|shefteli}}, {{t|lad|brisko}}\n* Lao: {{t|lo|ໝາກພິດຄ}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|persicum|n}}, {{t|la|duracinum|n}}\n* Latvian: {{t+|lv|persiks|m}}, {{t|lv|firziķis|m}}\n* Laz: {{t|lzz|ანტამა}}\n* Ligurian: {{t|lij|pèrsego}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t+|lt|persikas|m}}\n* Lombard: {{t|lmo|persich}}, {{t|lmo|persegh}}, {{t|lmo|pérsigh}}\n* Low German: {{t|nds|Peersch|m}}\n*: East Frisian Low German: {{t|frs|peerske|n}}, {{t|frs|paarske|n}} {{qualifier|Emden}}\n* Lü: {{t|khb|ᦖᦱᧅᦃᦸᧂᧈ}}\n* Luxembourgish: {{t|lb|Piisch|f}}, {{t|lb|Pijen|p}}\n* Macanese: {{t|mzs|péscu}}\n* Macedonian: {{t+|mk|пра́ска|f}}\n* Malagasy: {{t+|mg|paiso}}\n* Malay: {{t|ms|pic}}, {{t|ms|persik}}\n* Maltese: {{t|mt|ħawħ|m}}, {{t|mt|ħawħa|f}}\n* Manchu: {{t|mnc|ᡨᠣᡵᠣ}}\n* Manx: {{t|gv|peitshag}}, {{t|gv|pershagh}}\n* Māori: {{t+|mi|pītiti}}\n* Mirandese: {{t+|mwl|pierxigo|m}}, {{t+|mwl|piérxigo|m}}\n* Mongolian: {{t+|mn|тоор}}, {{t|mn|тоор жимс}}, {{t|mn|персик}}\n* Navajo: {{t|nv|didzétsoh}}, {{t|nv|bitseeʼ hólóní}}\n* Neapolitan: {{t|nap|pèrzeca}}, {{t|nap|percòca}}, {{t|nap|piérzeco}}\n* Nogai: {{t|nog|шабдал}}\n* Norman: {{t|nrf|pêche|f}}\n* Norwegian: {{t|no|fersken|m}}\n* Occitan: {{t+|oc|persèga|f}}, {{t+|oc|persec|m}}\n* Ojibwe: {{t|oj|miishijiimin}}\n* Okinawan: {{t|ryu|桃|tr=むむ, mumu}}\n* Old English: {{t|ang|persoc|m}}\n* Oromo: {{t|om|kookii}}\n* Pannonian Rusyn: {{t|rsk|брескиня|f}}\n* Pashto: {{t|ps|شلتالو|m|tr=shaltâlu}}, {{t+|ps|شوتالو|m|tr=šawtâlu}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|هلو|tr=holu}}, {{t+|fa|شفتالو|tr=šaftâlu}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|brzoskwinia|f}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|pêssego|m}}\n* Quechua: {{t|qu|turasnu}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|piersică|f}}\n* Romansh: {{t|rm|persic|m}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|пе́рсик|m}}\n* Saaroa: {{t|sxr|mimiliki’ukuhlucu}}\n* Sami:\n*: Northern Sami: {{t|se|persihkka}}\n* Sardinian:\n*: Campidanese: {{t|sc|prèssiu|m}}\n*: Logudorese: {{t|sc|pèssighe|m}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|peitseag|f}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|бре̏сква|f}}\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|brȅskva|f}}\n* Sicilian: {{t+|scn|pèrsicu|m}}\n* Sindhi: {{t|sd|آڙو}}\n* Slovak: {{t+|sk|broskyňa|f}}\n* Slovene: {{t+|sl|breskev|f}}\n* Sorbian:\n*: Lower Sorbian: {{t|dsb|rjaschen|m}}\n*: Upper Sorbian: {{t|hsb|brěšk|m}}, {{t|hsb|brěška|f}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|durazno|m}} {{qualifier|Mexico|Argentina}}, {{t+|es|melocotón|m}} {{qualifier|Antilles|Colombia|Dominican Republic|Spain}}\n* Swahili: {{t|sw|pichi}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|persika|c}}\n* Tagalog: {{t|tl|melokoton}}\n* Tajik: {{t+|tg|шафтолу}}\n* Taos: {{t|twf|phòʼína}}\n* Thai: {{t+|th|ท้อ}}, {{t|th|พีช}}\n* Tigrinya: {{t|ti|ኩኽ}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|şeftali}}, {{t+|tr|alıç}}\n* Turkmen: {{t|tk|şetdaly}}\n* Ubykh: {{t|uby|тым'а}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|пе́рсик|m}}\n* Unami: {{t|unm|pilkësh}}\n* Urdu: {{t+|ur|آڑو|tr=āṛū}}\n* Uyghur: {{t|ug|شاپتۇل}}\n* Uzbek: {{t+|uz|shaftoli}}\n* Venetan: {{t+|vec|pèrsego}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|đào}}\n* Volapük: {{t+|vo|pärsig}}\n* Welsh: {{t+|cy|eirinen wlanog|f}}\n* Winnebago: {{t|win|kšeehįšek}}, {{t|win|kąąc hįšek|lit=fuzzy plum}}\n* Yiddish: {{t|yi|פֿערשקע|f}}\n* Zazaki: {{t|zza|xewx}}\n* Zulu: {{t+|zu|ipentshisi}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|colour}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t|af|perkse}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|préssec|m}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|persikka}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|pêche|f}}\n* Frisian:\n*: West Frisian: {{t|fy|pjisk|n}}, {{t|fy|perzik|c}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|ატმისფერი}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|ροδακινί|n}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|krem}}\n* Italian: {{t|it|color pesca}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|桃色|tr=ももいろ, momoiro}}\n* Macedonian: {{t+|mk|пра́ска|f}}\n* Norwegian: {{t|no|fersken|m}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|brzoskwiniowy|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t|pt|cor [[pêssego]]|f}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|piersiciu}} {{qualifier|rare}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|пе́рсик|m}}, {{t+|ru|пе́рсиковый|m}} {{qualifier|цвет}}\n* Sicilian: {{t+|scn|pèrsicu|m}}\n* Volapük: {{t|vo|pärsigaköl}}\n* Welsh: {{t|cy|melynbinc}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|pleasing person/thing}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|красавица|f}}\n* Japanese: {{t|ja|[[すてき]]な[[人]]|tr=sutekina hito}}, {{t|ja|[[すてき]][[もの]]|tr=sutekina mono}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t+|nb|perle|m|f}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|هلو|tr=holu}}\n* Spanish: {{t|es|perita en dulce|f}} {{qualifier|colloquial}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Adjective====\n{{en-adj}}\n\n# Of or pertaining to the {{l|en|color}} peach.\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=The Naked Wall|author=Anne Bold-Pryor|year=2006|passage=Looking around her very large and very '''peach''' open kitchen and family room, I couldn't believe my eyes, but I knew the color must be there for a reason.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZHpzOu14DE8C&lpg=PA50&dq=%22very%20peach%22&pg=PA50#v=onepage&q=%22very%20peach%22&f=false}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=It Happened on a Train|year=2012|author=Mac Barnett|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o0WG_NeX0F4C&lpg=PA124&dq=%22very%20peach%22&pg=PA124#v=onepage&q=%22very%20peach%22&f=false|passage=The dining compartment was very '''peach'''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Happy Clouds, Happy Trees: The Bob Ross Phenomenon|author=Kristin G. Congdon|year=2014|url=|passage=Perhaps this is best illustrated in the particularly bizarre Kinkade painting entitled The Good Shepherd's Cottage, where an openarmed (and very '''peach''') Jesus welcomes a herd of sheep—literal sheep—to the threshold of a glowing cottage.}}\n# Particularly {{l|en|pleasing}} or {{l|en|agreeable}}.\n#: {{syn|en|agreeable|fair|orange|paragon|peachy|rosy}}\n#: {{ant|en|disagreeable|foul|ugly|unpleasant}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2000|title=Afraid to Death|author=Marc Behm |page=174| ISBN=1901982653| passage='That'll be just '''peach''' with me.'}}\n#* {{quote-newsgroup|en|date=May 19, 2011|author=Gilbert Sullivan|title=SWF (Adobe Flash) support|url=https://groups.google.com/forum/#!search/%22peach$20with$20me%22/linux.debian.user/LT2GYtVXrss/pOjdIj0Zg5oJ|newsgroup=linux.debian.user|passage=If I explain that I won't help them maintain systems running proprietary software (I'll make an exception for firmware, sometimes.) they usually shrug their shoulders and ask someone else -- which is just '''peach''' with me.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2011 |title=Ultraviolet |author=R. J. Anderson |page=9 |ISBN=0761374086 |passage=Her words were '''peach''' with sincerity, and I could tell she really believed it was a good idea. }}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=November 2, 2015|work=From Athlete to triathlete|title=Resetting, goalsetting, and dreamsetting |passage=I am sure I was just '''peach''' to deal with.}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|colour}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t|af|perskekleurig}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|krem}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|peitseagach}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|пе́рсиковий}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|mul|🍑}}\n* {{l|en|laetrile}}\n* {{l|en|nectarine}}\n* [[Appendix:Colors]]\n\n====Further reading====\n* {{pedia|Peach}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|pechen}}, from {{m|enm|apechen||to accuse}} and {{m|enm|empechen||to accuse}}, possibly from {{der|en|xno|anpecher}}, from {{der|en|la-lat|impedicō||entangle}}. See [[impeach]].\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|obsolete}} To inform on someone; turn informer.\n#: {{syn|en|sing|squeal|tattle|Thesaurus:rat out}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Shakespeare|title=Henry IV|year=1623|passage=If I be ta'en, I'll '''peach''' for this.}}\n#* {{RQ:Meredith Richard Feverel||9||\"But will your cousin tell?\" was Ripton's reflection.<br>\"He!\" Richard's lip expressed contempt. \"A ploughman refuses to '''peach''', and you ask if a Feverel will?\"}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1916|author=w:James Joyce|title=w:Portrait of the Artist as a Young Man|publisher=Macmillan Press Ltd|edition=paperback|page=21|passage=And his father had told him if he ever wanted anything to write home to him and, whatever he did, never to '''peach''' on a fellow.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1913|author=w:Rex Stout|title=Her Forbidden Knight|year_published=1997|publisher={{w|Carroll & Graf Publishers|Carroll & Graf}}|isbn=0786704446|page=123|passage=\"Do you think we want to '''peach'''? No, thank you. We may be none too good, but we won't hang a guy up, no matter who he is.{{...}}\"}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To {{l|en|inform}} against.\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic of the Reign of Henry VIII|year=1535|year_published=1886|volume=9|page=387|passage=Complaining of the conduct of Sir Ralph Robinson, parson of Brede, in Sussex, who took from him a psalter book in English, printed ''cum privilegio regali'', and '''peached''' him of heresy, whereupon he was put in the stocks by the King's constable for two days.|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=glY4AQAAMAAJ&dq=%22peached%20him%22&pg=PA387#v=onepage&q=%22peached%20him%22&f=false}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|magazine=London Magazine|volume=43|year=1774|page=639|title=The British Theatre|passage={{...}} and finding out the residence of his brother Charles, desires him not to '''''peach''''' him, but to lend him a suit of his fine cloaths, that he might see what it was to be a fine gentleman {{...}}}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Life of Colonel Jack: And, a True Relation of the Apparition of One Mrs. Veal|author=Daniel Defoe|year=1840|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gKIsAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22peached%20me%22&pg=PA77#v=onepage&q=%22peached%20me%22&f=false|passage=Ay, says Will, I am undone for all that; for the officers are after me; and I am a dead dog if I am taken, for George is in custody, and he has '''peached''' me and all the others, to save his life.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|peacher}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|to inform on someone}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|доноснича}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|práskat|impf}}, {{t+|cs|bonzovat|impf}}, {{t+|cs|žalovat|impf}}, {{t+|cs|prásknout|pf}} (koho), {{t+|cs|udávat|impf}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|beárul}}, {{t+|hu|beköp}}, {{t+|hu|besúg}}, {{t+|hu|befúj}}, {{t+|hu|spicliskedik}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|я́бедничать|impf}}, {{t+|ru|доноси́ть|impf}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|-}}\n\n# {{lb|en|mineralogy|obsolete|Cornwall}} A particular {{l|en|rock}} found in {{l|en|tin}} mines, sometimes associated with {{l|en|chlorite}}.\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Manual of the mineralogy of Great Britain & Ireland|author=Robert Philips Greg|year=1858|passage=Chlorite forms the characterizing ingredient in chlorite slate; it is common in Cornwall with the tin veins, constituting with quartz the rock commonly known there as ''killas''; the ordinary name for chlorite is '''''peach'''''.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n-MJAAAAIAAJ&dq=%22peach%22%20%22chlorite%22&pg=PA199#v=onepage&q=%22peach%22%20%22chlorite%22&f=false}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|magazine=The Mining and Smelting Magazine|title=Illustrated Notes on Prominent Mines|page=17|volume=2|passage='''Peach''', which is a word used by the Cornish miners, in a generic sense, to denote all minerals of the chloritic family—and is consequently a very convenient word—seems to be essentially the \"mother\" of tin; but the experience of Cornwall goes to show that '''peach''' alone does not produce a permanent tin mine: an intermixture of quartz is necessary to give what miners call \"strength\" to the lode.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x8M_AQAAMAAJ&dq=%22peach%22%20%22mining%22%20%22tin%22&pg=PA17#v=onepage&q=%22peach%22%20%22mining%22%20%22tin%22&f=false|year=1862}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=The Geology of Falmouth and Truro and of the Mining District of Camborne and Redruth|author=James Bastian Hill|year=1908|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vDbPAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22peach%22%20%22chlorite%22&pg=PA155#v=onepage&q=%22peach%22%20%22chlorite%22&f=false|passage=A quartz (sparry) vein, unless accompanied by other minerals such as '''peach''', chlorite, &c., is considered valueless as an indication of the presence of ore.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|blue peach}}\n* {{l|en|green peach}}\n* {{l|en|peach tourmaline}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=acehp|Pecha|chape|chapé|cheap}}\n\n{{C|en|Fruits|Oranges|Pinks|Prunus genus plants}}\n{{cln|en|terms derived from toponyms}}"}}